WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.860
This is a LibriVox recording. All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain. For more

00:07.860 --> 00:14.300
information or to find out how you can volunteer, please visit LibriVox.org.

00:14.300 --> 00:17.620
THE PICTURE OF DORIAN GREY

00:30.460 --> 00:31.700
CHAPTER VIII

00:32.320 --> 00:37.700
When his servant entered, he looked at him steadfastly, and wondered if he had thought

00:37.700 --> 00:43.200
of peering behind the screen. The man was quite impassive and waited for his orders.

00:44.240 --> 00:49.560
Dorian lit a cigarette and walked over to the glass and glanced into it. He could see

00:49.560 --> 00:56.300
the reflection of Victor's face perfectly. It was like a placid mask of servility. There

00:56.300 --> 01:02.760
was nothing to be afraid of there, yet he thought it best to be on his guard. Speaking

01:02.760 --> 01:09.280
very slowly, he told him to tell the housekeeper that he wanted to see her, and then to go

01:09.280 --> 01:14.560
to the frame-makers and ask him to send two of his men round at once. It seemed to him

01:14.560 --> 01:20.420
that as the man left the room he peered in the direction of the screen, or was that only

01:20.420 --> 01:21.160
his fancy?

01:22.100 --> 01:27.900
After a few moments Mrs. Leaf, a dear old lady in a black silk dress with a photograph

01:27.900 --> 01:33.400
of the late Mr. Leaf framed in a large gold brooch at her neck, and an old-fashioned

01:33.400 --> 01:37.000
thread mittens on her wrinkled hands bustled into the room.

01:38.040 --> 01:43.000
Well, Master Dorian, she said, what can I do for you? I beg your pardon, sir. Here came

01:43.000 --> 01:47.820
a courtesy. I shouldn't call you Master Dorian any more, but, Lord bless you, sir, I have

01:47.820 --> 01:52.380
known you since you were a baby. And many's the trick you've played on poor old Leaf.

01:52.380 --> 01:57.980
Not that you are not always a good boy, sir, but boys will be boys, Master Dorian, and

01:57.980 --> 02:01.800
jam is a temptation to the young, isn't it, sir?' He laughed.

02:02.540 --> 02:08.880
"'You must always call me Master Dorian, Leaf. I will be very angry with you if you don't.

02:08.980 --> 02:14.500
And I assure you I am quite as fond of jam now as I used to be. Only when I am asked

02:14.500 --> 02:19.640
out to tea I am never offered any. I want you to give me the key of the room at the

02:19.640 --> 02:20.720
top of the house.'

02:20.720 --> 02:26.400
"'The old school-room, Master Dorian? Why, it's full of dust. I must get it arranged

02:26.400 --> 02:30.320
and put straight before you get into it. It is not fit for you to see, Master Dorian.

02:30.340 --> 02:35.240
It is not, indeed. I don't want it put straight. Leaf, I only want the key.'

02:36.380 --> 02:41.760
"'Well, Master Dorian, you'll be covered with cobwebs if you goes into it. Why, it hasn't

02:41.760 --> 02:46.420
been open for nearly five years, not since his lordship died.'

02:46.420 --> 02:51.440
He winced at the mention of his dead uncle's name. He had hateful memories of him.

02:52.200 --> 02:57.200
"'That does not matter, Leaf,' he replied. All I want is the key.'

02:57.200 --> 03:01.800
"'And here is the key, Master Dorian,' said the old lady, after going over the contents

03:01.800 --> 03:07.600
of a bunch with tremulously uncertain hands. Here is the key. I'll have it off the ring

03:07.600 --> 03:12.220
in a moment, but you don't think of living up there, Master Dorian, and you're so comfortable

03:12.220 --> 03:12.800
here.'

03:12.800 --> 03:17.880
"'No, Leaf, I don't. I merely want to see the place, and perhaps store something in it.

03:17.960 --> 03:24.300
That is all. Thank you, Leaf. I hope your rheumatism is better. And mind you, send me

03:24.300 --> 03:29.680
up jam for breakfast.' Mrs. Leaf shook her head. Them foreigners don't understand jam,

03:29.680 --> 03:35.740
Master Dorian. They calls it compot. But I'll bring it to you myself some morning, if you

03:35.740 --> 03:36.860
lets me.'

03:36.860 --> 03:41.640
"'That will be very kind of you, Leaf,' he answered, looking at the key, and having

03:41.640 --> 03:47.180
made him an elaborate courtesy, the old lady left the room, her face wreathed in smiles.

03:48.080 --> 03:53.380
She had a strong objection to the French valet. It was a poor thing, she felt, for anyone

03:53.380 --> 03:59.840
to be born a foreigner. As the door closed, Dorian put the key in his pocket and looked

03:59.840 --> 04:05.620
round the room. His eye fell on a large purple satin coverlet heavily embroidered with gold,

04:05.840 --> 04:10.720
a splendid piece of late seventeenth-century Venetian work that his uncle had found in

04:10.720 --> 04:17.400
a convent near Bologna. Yes, that would serve to wrap the dreadful thing in. It had perhaps

04:17.400 --> 04:22.480
served often as a pall for the dead. Now it was to hide something that had a corruption

04:22.480 --> 04:28.340
of its own, worse than the corruption of death itself, something that would breed horrors

04:28.340 --> 04:30.040
and yet would never die.

04:31.620 --> 04:36.820
What the worm was to the corpse, his sins would be to the painted image on the canvas.

04:37.370 --> 04:42.680
They would mar its beauty and eat away its grace. They would defile it and make it shameful.

04:43.560 --> 04:49.140
And yet the thing would still live on. It would always be alive.

04:50.320 --> 04:55.040
He shuddered, and for a moment he regretted that he had not told Basil the true reason

04:55.040 --> 05:00.220
why he had wished to hide the picture away. Basil would have helped him to resist Lord

05:00.220 --> 05:05.600
Henry's influence, and the still more poisonous influences that came from his own temperament,

05:06.220 --> 05:12.460
the love that he bore him, for it was really love, had something noble and intellectual

05:12.460 --> 05:19.000
in it. It was not that merely physical admiration of beauty that is born of the senses and that

05:19.000 --> 05:25.740
dies when the senses tire. It was such a love as Michelangelo had known, and Montaigne and

05:25.740 --> 05:31.760
Winkleman and Shakespeare himself. Yes, Basil could have saved him, but it was too late

05:31.760 --> 05:32.200
now.

05:33.280 --> 05:40.940
The past could always be annihilated. Regret, denial, or forgetfulness could do that. But

05:40.940 --> 05:47.640
the future was inevitable. There were passions in him that would find their terrible outlet,

05:49.100 --> 05:52.760
dreams that would make the shadow of their evil real.

05:53.480 --> 05:58.200
He took up from the couch the great purple and gold texture that covered it, and, holding

05:58.200 --> 06:04.720
it in his hands, passed behind the screen. Was the face on the canvas viler than before?

06:05.760 --> 06:11.220
It seemed to him that it was unchanged, and yet his loathing of it was intensified. Gold

06:11.220 --> 06:18.760
hair, blue eyes, and rose-red lips, they all were there. It was simply the expression that

06:18.760 --> 06:28.180
had altered. That was horrible in its cruelty. Compared to what he saw in it of censure or

06:28.180 --> 06:33.900
Basil's reproaches about Sibyl Vane had been, how shallow, and of what little account. His

06:33.900 --> 06:39.780
own soul was looking out at him from the canvas and calling him to judgment. A look of pain

06:39.780 --> 06:45.500
came across him, and he flung the rich pall over the picture. As he did so, a knock came

06:45.500 --> 06:48.840
to the door. He passed out as his servant entered.

06:49.620 --> 06:55.560
The persons are here, monsieur. He felt that the man must be got rid of at once. He must

06:55.560 --> 07:00.400
not be allowed to know where the picture was being taken to. There was something sly about

07:00.400 --> 07:06.700
him, and yet thoughtful, treacherous eyes. Sitting down at the writing-table, he scribbled

07:06.700 --> 07:11.080
a note to Lord Henry, asking him to send round something to read, and reminding him that

07:11.080 --> 07:13.220
they were to meet at eight-fifteen that evening.

07:14.040 --> 07:19.660
"'Wait for an answer,' he said, handing it to him, and, "'Show the men in here.' In two

07:19.660 --> 07:24.360
or three minutes there was another knock, and Mr. Ashton himself, the celebrated frame-maker

07:24.360 --> 07:31.100
of South Audley Street, came in with a somewhat rough-looking young assistant. Mr. Ashton

07:31.100 --> 07:37.680
was a florid red-whiskered little man, whose admiration for art was considerably tempered

07:37.680 --> 07:45.380
by the inveterate impeccuinosity of most of the artists who dealt with him. As a rule,

07:45.620 --> 07:51.440
he never left his shop. He waited for people to come to him, but he always made an exception

07:51.440 --> 07:56.720
in favour of Dorian Gray. There was something about Dorian that charmed everybody. It was

07:56.720 --> 07:58.320
a pleasure even to see him.

07:59.800 --> 08:05.120
"'What can I do for you, Mr. Gray?' he said, rubbing his fat freckled hands.

08:05.380 --> 08:11.160
"'I thought I would do myself the honour of coming round in person. I have just got

08:11.160 --> 08:17.160
a beauty of a frame, sir, picked it up at a sale, old Florentine. Came from Fontill,

08:17.160 --> 08:24.160
I believe. Admirably suited for a religious picture, Mr. Gray. I'm sorry you have given

08:24.160 --> 08:28.440
yourself the trouble of coming round, Mr. Ashton. I will certainly drop in and look

08:28.440 --> 08:33.320
at the frame, though I don't go in much for religious art, but to-day I only want a picture

08:33.320 --> 08:37.920
carried to the top of the house for me. It is rather heavy, so I thought I would ask

08:37.920 --> 08:39.880
you to lend me a couple of your men.'

08:39.880 --> 08:46.340
"'No trouble at all, Mr. Gray. I am delighted to be of any service to you. Which is the

08:46.340 --> 08:48.480
work of art, sir?'

08:48.480 --> 08:51.780
"'This,' replied Dorian, moving the screen back.

08:52.100 --> 08:56.680
"'Can you move it, covering it all, just as it is? I don't want it to get scratched

08:56.680 --> 08:57.700
going upstairs.'

08:58.360 --> 09:03.160
"'There will be no difficulty, sir,' said the genial frame-maker, beginning, with the

09:03.160 --> 09:08.100
aid of his assistant, to unhook the picture from the long brass chain by which it was

09:08.100 --> 09:16.320
suspended. And now where shall we carry it to, Mr. Gray? I will show you the way, Mr.

09:16.320 --> 09:20.620
Ashton. Perhaps you better go in front. I am afraid it is right at the top of the house.

09:20.940 --> 09:25.340
You will go up at the front staircase, as it is wider.'

09:25.340 --> 09:30.760
He held the door open for them, and they passed out into the hall and began the ascent. The

09:30.760 --> 09:36.760
elaborate character of the frame has made the picture extremely bulky. And now and then,

09:36.900 --> 09:42.120
in spite of the obsequious protests of Mr. Ashton, who had a true tradesman's dislike

09:42.120 --> 09:47.840
of seeing a gentleman do anything useful, Dorian put his hand to it so as to help them.

09:48.660 --> 09:53.500
"'Something of a load to carry, sir,' gasped the little man, when they reached the top

09:53.500 --> 09:55.980
landing, and he wiped his shiny forehead.

09:56.620 --> 10:02.060
"'A terrible load to carry,' murmured Dorian, as he unlocked the door that opened into the

10:02.060 --> 10:07.680
room that was to keep for him the curious secret of his life and hide his soul from

10:07.680 --> 10:09.080
the eyes of men.

10:10.480 --> 10:16.500
"'He had not entered the place for more than four years. Not, indeed, since he had used

10:16.500 --> 10:21.140
it first as a playroom when he was a child, and then as a study when he grew somewhat

10:21.140 --> 10:27.440
older. It was a large, well-proportioned room which had been specially built by the last

10:27.440 --> 10:32.800
Lord Sherrod, for the use of the little nephew whom, being himself childless, and perhaps

10:32.800 --> 10:38.540
for other reasons, he had always hated and desired to keep at a distance. It did not

10:38.540 --> 10:45.240
appear to Dorian to have much changed. There was the huge Italian casson with its fantastically

10:45.240 --> 10:51.140
painted panels and its tarnished gilt mouldings, in which he had so often hidden himself as

10:51.140 --> 10:56.840
a boy. There was a satin-wood bookcase filled with his dogged school books. On the wall

10:56.840 --> 11:03.160
behind it was hanging the same ragged Flemish tapestry where a faded king and queen were

11:03.160 --> 11:08.180
playing chess in a garden while a company of hawkers rode by carrying hooded birds on

11:08.180 --> 11:15.200
their gauntleted wrists. How well he recalled it all! Every moment of his lonely childhood

11:15.200 --> 11:21.040
came back to him as he looked round. He remembered the stainless purity of his boyish life, and

11:21.040 --> 11:25.960
it seemed horrible to him that it was here that the fatal portrait was to be hidden away.

11:26.520 --> 11:34.100
How little he had thought in those dead days of all that was in store for him! But there

11:34.100 --> 11:38.400
was no other place in the house so secure from prying eyes as this. He had the key,

11:38.440 --> 11:44.180
and no one else could enter it. Beneath its purple pall, the face painted on the canvas

11:44.180 --> 11:50.700
could grow bestial, sodden and unclean. What did it matter? No one could see it. He himself

11:50.700 --> 11:56.220
would not see it. Why should he watch the hideous corruption of his soul? He kept his

11:56.220 --> 12:02.940
youth, that was enough. And besides, might not his nature grow finer after all? There

12:02.940 --> 12:08.600
was no reason that the future should be so full of shame. Some love might come across

12:08.600 --> 12:14.080
his life and purify him, and shield him from those sins that seemed to be already stirring

12:14.080 --> 12:21.760
in spirit and in flesh, those curious unpictured sins whose very mystery lent them their subtlety

12:21.760 --> 12:28.300
and their charm. Perhaps, some day, the cruel look would have passed away from the scarlet's

12:28.300 --> 12:35.940
sensitive mouth, and he might show to the world Basil Hallward's masterpiece. No, that

12:35.940 --> 12:41.460
was impossible. The thing upon the canvas was growing old, hour by hour and week by

12:41.460 --> 12:48.580
week. Even if it escaped the hideousness of sin, the hideousness of age was in store for

12:48.580 --> 12:58.160
it. The cheeks would become hollow or flaccid. The yellow crow's feet would creep round the

12:58.160 --> 13:04.720
brightness. The mouth would gape, droop, would be foolish or gross as the mouths of

13:04.720 --> 13:11.280
old men are. There would be the wrinkled throat, the cold, blue-veined hands, the twisted body

13:11.280 --> 13:18.120
that he remembered in the uncle who had been so stern to him in his boyhood. The picture

13:18.120 --> 13:22.260
had to be concealed. There was no help for it.

13:22.820 --> 13:27.020
"'Bring it in, Mr. Ashton, please,' he said, wearily, turning around.

13:27.720 --> 13:32.240
"'I'm sorry I kept you so long. I was thinking of something else.'

13:32.240 --> 13:37.400
"'Always glad to have a rest, Mr. Grey,' answered the frame-maker, who was still gasping

13:37.400 --> 13:40.240
for breath. "'Where shall we put it, sir?'

13:40.240 --> 13:45.420
"'Oh, anywhere. Here, this will do. I don't want to have it hung up. Just lean it against

13:45.420 --> 13:51.200
the wall. Thanks. Might one look at the work of art, sir?' Dorian started.

13:52.220 --> 13:57.420
"'It would not interest you, Mr. Ashton,' he said, keeping his eye on the old man. He

13:57.420 --> 14:01.240
felt ready to leap on him and fling him to the ground if he dared to lift the gorgeous

14:01.240 --> 14:03.440
hanging that concealed the secret of his life.

14:04.400 --> 14:08.520
"'I won't trouble you any more now. I am much obliged for your kindness in coming round.'

14:09.460 --> 14:13.920
"'Not at all, not at all, Mr. Grey. Ever ready to do anything for you, sir?'

14:13.920 --> 14:18.620
And Mr. Ashton trapped downstairs, followed by the assistant, who glanced back at Dorian

14:18.620 --> 14:25.560
with a look of shy wonder in his rough, uncomely face. He had never seen anyone so marvellous.

14:27.760 --> 14:32.320
When the sound of their footsteps had died away, Dorian locked the door and put the key

14:32.320 --> 14:39.720
in his pocket. He felt safe now. No one would ever look on the horrible thing. No eye but

14:39.720 --> 14:41.940
his would ever see his shame.

14:43.160 --> 14:47.660
On reaching the library he found that it was after five o'clock, and that the tea had already

14:47.660 --> 14:54.480
been brought up. On a little table of dark-perfumed wood thickly encrusted with nakra, a present

14:54.480 --> 15:00.400
from his guardian's wife, Lady Radley, who had spent the preceding winter in Cairo, was

15:00.400 --> 15:06.020
lying a note from Lord Henry, and beside it was a book bound in yellow paper, the cover

15:06.020 --> 15:12.080
slightly torn and the edges soiled. A copy of the third edition of St. James's Gazette

15:12.080 --> 15:18.480
had been placed on the tea-tray. It was evident that Victor had returned. He wondered if he

15:18.480 --> 15:22.760
had met the men in the hall as they were leaving the house, and had wormed out of them what

15:22.760 --> 15:27.760
they had been doing. He would be sure to miss the picture, had no doubt missed it already

15:27.760 --> 15:32.840
while he had been laying the tea-things. The screen had not been replaced, and the blank

15:32.840 --> 15:37.900
space on the wall was visible. Perhaps some night he might find him creeping upstairs

15:37.900 --> 15:43.200
and trying to force the door of the room. It was a horrible thing to have a spy in

15:43.200 --> 15:47.560
one's house. He had heard of rich men who had been blackmailed all their lives by some

15:47.560 --> 15:52.980
servant who had read a letter, or overheard a conversation, or picked up a card with an

15:52.980 --> 16:00.220
address, or found beneath a pillow a withered flower, or a bit of crumpled lace. He sighed,

16:00.620 --> 16:05.860
and having poured himself out some tea, opened Lord Henry's note. It was simply to say that

16:05.860 --> 16:10.560
he sent him round the evening paper and a book that might interest him, and that he

16:10.560 --> 16:15.620
would be at the club at eight fifteen. He opened the St. James's Langwoodly and looked

16:15.620 --> 16:20.500
through it. A red pencil mark on the fifth page caught his eye. He read the following

16:20.500 --> 16:21.220
paragraph.

16:23.080 --> 16:24.860
Inquest on an Actress

16:24.860 --> 16:31.000
An inquest was held this morning at the Bell Tavern, Hoxton Road, by Mr. Danby, the District

16:31.000 --> 16:37.020
Coroner, on the body of Sybil Vane, a young actress recently engaged at the Royal Theatre

16:37.020 --> 16:38.140
Holburne.

16:38.820 --> 16:44.560
A verdict of death by misadventure was returned. Considerable sympathy was expressed for the

16:44.560 --> 16:49.760
mother of the deceased, who was greatly affected during the giving of her own evidence, and

16:49.760 --> 16:56.960
that of Dr. Birel, who had made the post-mortem examination of the deceased. He frowned slightly,

16:57.360 --> 17:02.000
and tearing the paper in two, went across the room and flung the pieces into a gilt

17:02.000 --> 17:09.460
basket. How ugly it all was, and how horribly real ugliness made things! He felt a little

17:09.460 --> 17:13.720
annoyed with Lord Henry for having sent him the account, and it was certainly stupid of

17:13.720 --> 17:19.840
him to have marked it with a red pencil. Victor might have read it. The man knew more than

17:19.840 --> 17:26.140
enough English for that. Perhaps he had read it, and had begun to suspect something.

17:27.120 --> 17:27.660
And?

17:28.560 --> 17:34.080
And yet what did it matter? What had Dorian Gray to do with Sybil Vane's death? There

17:34.080 --> 17:40.280
was nothing to fear. Dorian Gray had not killed her. His eye fell on the yellow book that

17:40.280 --> 17:42.920
Lord Henry had sent him. What was it, he wondered?

17:43.420 --> 17:48.320
He went towards the little pearl-coloured octagonal stand that had always looked to

17:48.320 --> 17:54.400
him like the work of some strange Egyptian bees who rotten silver, and took the volume

17:54.400 --> 17:59.960
up. He flung himself into an arm-chair and began to turn over the leaves. After a few

17:59.960 --> 18:04.780
minutes he became absorbed. It was the strangest book he had ever read.

18:05.340 --> 18:11.380
It seemed to him that in exquisite raiment and to the delicate sound of flutes the sins

18:11.380 --> 18:18.560
of the world were passing in dumb show before him. Things that he had dimly dreamed of were

18:18.560 --> 18:24.260
suddenly made real to him. Things of which he had never dreamed were gradually revealed.

18:25.800 --> 18:33.000
It was a novel without a plot, and with only one character being, indeed, simply a psychological

18:33.000 --> 18:38.960
study of a certain young Parisian who spent his life trying to realise in the nineteenth

18:38.960 --> 18:44.320
century all the passions and modes of thought that belonged to every century except his

18:44.320 --> 18:50.280
own, and to sum up, as it were, in himself the various moods through which the world's

18:50.280 --> 18:56.960
spirit had ever passed, loving, for their mere artificiality, those renunciations that

18:56.960 --> 19:03.560
men had unwisely called virtue, as much as those natural rebellions that wise men still

19:03.560 --> 19:10.450
call sin. The style in which it was written was that curious jeweled style, vivid and

19:10.450 --> 19:17.170
obscure at once, full of argot and archaisms, of technical expressions and of elaborate

19:17.170 --> 19:23.290
paraphrases that characterises the work of some of the finest artists of the French school

19:23.290 --> 19:31.670
of decadence. There were in it metaphors as monstrous as orchids and as evil in colour.

19:32.390 --> 19:39.090
The life of the senses were described in the terms of mystical philosophy. One hardly knew

19:39.090 --> 19:44.970
at times whether one was reading the spiritual ecstasies of some medieval saint or the morbid

19:44.970 --> 19:52.110
confessions of a modern sinner. It was a poisonous book. The heavy odour of incense seemed to

19:52.110 --> 19:57.970
cling about its pages and to trouble the brain. The mere cadence of the senses, the subtle

19:57.970 --> 20:04.430
monotony of their music, so full, as it was, of complex refrains and movements elaborately

20:04.430 --> 20:10.570
repeated, produced in the mind of the lad, as he passed from chapter to chapter, a form

20:10.570 --> 20:16.750
of reverie, a malady of dreaming, that made him unconscious of the falling day and the

20:16.750 --> 20:25.590
creeping shadows. Cloudless and pierced by one solitary star, a copper-green sky gleamed

20:25.590 --> 20:32.110
through the windows. He read on by its one light till he could read no more. Then, after

20:32.110 --> 20:37.170
his valet had reminded him several times of the lateness of the hour, he got up, and going

20:37.170 --> 20:42.070
into the next room placed the book on the little Florentine table that always stood

20:42.070 --> 20:47.970
at his bedside, and began to dress for dinner. It was almost nine o'clock before he reached

20:47.970 --> 20:53.190
the club, where he found Lord Henry sitting alone in the morning-room, looking very bored.

20:54.710 --> 21:00.230
"'I am so sorry, Harry,' he cried, "'but really it is entirely your fault. That book

21:00.230 --> 21:03.510
you sent me so fascinated me, I forgot what the time was.'

21:04.930 --> 21:09.570
"'I thought you would like it,' replied his host, rising from his chair.

21:10.150 --> 21:14.470
"'I didn't say I liked it, Harry, I said it fascinated me. There is a great difference.'

21:15.230 --> 21:21.190
"'Ah, if you have discovered that, you have discovered a great deal,' murmured Lord Henry,

21:21.230 --> 21:27.650
with his curious smile. "'Come, let us go into dinner. It is dreadfully late, and I am afraid

21:27.650 --> 21:38.150
the champagne will be too much iced.' End of chapter eight of the picture of Dorian

21:38.150 --> 21:38.530
Grey

